column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: At approximately 1345 the driver stopped at the Flying J truck stop in Kansas City, Mo and noticed the container leaking wet contents out of the gate. Upon arrival the emergency response team donned appropriate PPE, secured the area with plastic sheeting and removed the container from the transport vehicle. Members of the ER team entered the container and shoveled material away from the rear gate. They discovered an article of clothing lodged in the gate, disrupting the integrity of the seal. The gate was opened and the obstruction removed. Additional absorbent and liner material was placed in the container and the surrounding area was cleaned of all debris. Contractor personnel offloaded 800 gallons of the product and decontaminated the car.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1.    Cause Code: 529    NARRI Code: 5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: TILX 101029 was reported as leaking spent sulfuric acid by PTRA train crews at approximately 1530 hours central time on May 4, 2017 in the vicinity of the PTRA Pasadena Yard.  PTRA notified Rick Ferguson with Shell Chemical company and Shell dispatched OMI to the scene to inspect, repair and remediate the spill.  OMI personnel determined that the source of the leak was loose flange bolts on the liquid line. OMI responders tightened the bolts and inspected the liquid line cap and seal.  They observed no additional leakage after securing the car.  OMI then remediated the product on the sides of the tank car and the small area that had dripped onto the ballast. The scene was cleared by 1800 hours and the car was released for movement to destination.
column169: Shell Chemical is investigating the cause of the loose flange bolts on the liquid line.

column168: On 05/08/2017, at 1257 hours, an FRA Inspector in the CSXT Philadelphia East Side Yard discovered UTLX 959997, a loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gases, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and Williams Ohio Valley Midstream(Shipper), Philadelphia Fire Department, National Response Center, and the Pennsylvania Emergency Management Agency were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2017-05-08-000128). HEPACO, LLC of Philadelphia, PA, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the B End Liquid Line partially open and the secondary closure plug incorrectly installed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Chris Hanlon - (304)845-8406. Contractor personnel secured the valve and properly installed the secondary closure plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. column168: THE DELIVERY VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HWY. 83 WHEN A BLOWOUT OCCURRED ON THE LEFT REAR OF THE VEHICLE. THIS CAUSED THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND VEER OFF ONTO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY. ONCE THE VEHICLE LEFT THE HIGHWAY IT SANK INTO THE SOFT SHOULDER AND ROLLED OVER. THIS CRUSHED THE 330 GALLON IBC OF WCI2810W. THE IBC WAS A PLASTIC TANK WITH METAL CAGE SURROUNDING IT. AS THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER THE IBC WAS CRUSHED WHICH ALLOWED THE SECUREMENT TO THE TRUCK TO BE COMPROMISED. THE IBC SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO THE CAGE AND THE ENTIRE PLASTIC TANK.    Y AND L EARTH OUT OF TURPIN, OK WAS CONTACTED BY OK HIGHWAY PATROL AND CONDUCTED THE CLEANUP OF THE SITE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH A DIRT BERM PLACED AROUND THE IMMEDIATE AREA. THE SPILL WAS ON THE GROUND FOR APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS BEFORE CLEANUP BEGAN. APPROXIMATELY 70 TONS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND SENT TO SEWARD COUNTY LANDFILL IN LIBERAL, KS FOR DISPOSAL. AN ADDITIONAL 70 TONS OF CLEAN MATERIAL WAS BROUGHT BACK INTO REPLACE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND THE AREA WAS GRADED AND THEN COVERED WITH SOD.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS EQUIPMENT FAILURE. WE ARE WORKING TO HAVE ALL OF OUR DRIVERS RETRAINED ON PROPER VEHICLE INSPECTIONS TO HELP REDUCE THE RISK OF ANOTHER INCIDENT LIKE THIS. THE LOAD WAS SECURED PROPERLY, BUT DUE TO THE ROLLOVER IT WAS CRUSHED AND THEN RELEASED FROM THE VEHICLE. I WILL BE LOOKING INTO FABRICATING BETTER ROLLOVER DEVICES FOR THE BEDS OF THE TRUCKS TO HELP REDUCE THE RISK OF CARGO BEING CRUSHED IN THE EVENT OF A ROLLOVER INCIDENT.

column168: UTLX 631411 was rejected by Cyanco because of product on the side of the tank car. The car was returned to the Winnemucca yard and spotted for inspection.  Upon inspection the dried product indicated that the release occurred at the liquid line.The  liquid line valve was in the closed position and the plug was less then tool tight. I removed the plug to inspect the valve and found 1/2 inch of product on top of the valve, as soon as the plug was removed the product drained back into the tank car, through the closed valve. This indicates that the liquid valve is defective. New teflon was applied to the plug and then the plug was secured tool tight on the liquid valve. The release volume was approximately 5 liquid gallons.     Shipper Seal removed- X824494  UPRR Seal Applied- 0000193

55 Gal Poly Drum of Terraclean 5.0 Activated Peroxyacetic Acid had been rejected from the customer due to a missing vent cap that was reportedly pressurized and pushed off the drum. Approximately 8 liquid ounces was released and confined to the top of the drum only. An environmental contractor was dispatched and could not replace then vent cap. The contractor over packed that damaged drum and it was staged on site pending the shipper's disposition

column168: It was reported that a shipment arrived damaged and reports 3-50 lb poly bags were torn releasing approx. 10 lbs UN1486 to the floor of the trailer and the dock. Contractor over-packed the impacted bags and released product into 1-30 gallon poly over-pack and staged all waste in OS&D.

Intermodal container EMHU654196 arrived in the Norfolk Southern facility in Austell, GA and was found leaking product from the bottom of the container.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the load was found to have shifted and damaged 2 five gallon drums that leaked product into the container and on the ground.

DRIVER WAS PREPARING FOR A DELIVERY TO CUSTOMER AND DURING UNLOADING THE PRODUCTS AND HE FOUND A 5 GALLON JUG LEAKING LIQUID PRODUCT FROM THE JUG ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE JUG WAS ON 1 WOODEN PALLET WITH A NAIL STICKING UP OFF WOODEN PALLET CONTAINING 15 TOTAL PAILS OF THE PRODUCT IN QUESTION. THE PAIL HAD BEEN LOADED WITH THE OTHER PAILS ON A DEFECTIVE WOODEN PALLET BY SHIPPER WHO SHRINK WRAPPED THE 15 PAILS ON THE PALLET. THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE PALLET UNDETECTED BY THE ROSS DRIVER.    THE DRIVER CHECKED HIS DOCUMENT AND FOUND THE PRODUCT TO BE HM. HE THEN CALLED DISPATCH TO NOTIFY OF HM INCIDENT, REFERENCED EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK TO TAKE THE PROPER STEPS FOR DRIVER SAFETY & PROTECTION, CLEANUP, DISPOSAL OF THE RELEASED HM. HE CALLED HIS SAFETY DIRECTOR WHO CALLED SHIPPER/MANUFACTURER ACCU-CARE SUPPLY IN E. PROVIDENCE, RI AND HE SPOKE DIRECTLY WITH THE CHEMIST OF PRODUCT FOR INSTRUCTION FOR PROPER CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL OF THE HM MATERIAL. OUR ROSS EXPRESS DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO USE DRY EARTH OR SPEEDEE DRY TO CLEAN UP THE LEAKED PRODUCT-POOL CHEMICAL AND SECURE IN A BAG FOR DISPOSAL, THEN USE WATER TO DILUTE THE REMAINING RESIDUE ON THE WOODEN TRAILER FLOOR. ONCE DILUTED THE PRODUCT HAS NO DANGER TO HUMANS. THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT BACK IMMEDIATELY TO NH SHOP FROM MAINE AND PLACED IN THE YARD TO BE EXPOSED TO THE AIR FOR VENTING AWAY THE CHLORINE SMELL. NO WATER WAS USED TO CLEANUP THE RESIDUE THAT NEEDED TO BE DISPOSED OF AS THE TRAILER WAS LEFT IN THE YARD TO VENT AND DRY OUT BEFORE ITS NEXT USE. NO OUTSIDE VENDOR WAS NEEDED TO COMPLETE CLEANUP AND NO FILE OR POLICE WERE INVOLVED WITH THIS HM INCIDENT. NO FAULT WAS DETERMINED BY THE ROSS EXPRESS DRIVER BUT A SHIPPER LOAD PREPARING ISSUE WAS FOUND FROM OUR INVESTIGATION.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 5/4/17 at approximately 17:18, outbound crew on the H BARBEL1 03A identified the PCVX 13371 as leaking from the top of the car.  The BNSF dispatcher notified the NOC and SID to initiate a response.  BNSF Officers responded to the scene to meet with the Kingman/Yucca Fire HM team.  Safe access was provided to the car for the FD to assess.  BNSF also dispatched a Hazmat contractor from Phoenix, AZ and a BNSF Hazmat Responder from Needles, CA.  The car was found to have a leak coming from the liquid line on the car.  The Fire Department attempted to tighten the flange bolts and plug which slowed the leak significantly.  Once the contractor arrived on-site, the pressure was bled from the car and the flange was removed for cleaning/inspection.  The sealing area was found to be corroded and the gasket appeared damaged.  Responders cleaned the sealing surface, applied a temporary gasket and re-secured the car.  The car was neutralized using sodium bicarbonate and water, surfaces and the ballast were pH and found to be neutral after the cleaning process.  The car was inspected and allowed to travel to destination (approximately 16 miles from the siding location).
column169: Shipper should ensure that all valves/fittings on cars are secured and leak free before placement into transportation.  Please review with loading personnel.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 5/4/17 at approximately 17:37, a citizen reported to the BNSF ROCC that tank car PROX 47317 was leaking while in the yard at Great Falls, MT.  BNSF transportation and mechanical hazmat responders assessed the report and determined that the car was actively leaking from the protective housing.  The Great Falls Fire Department and Calumet responders also responded to assist.  The car was isolate, secured and employees removed from the area.  Hazmat responders determined that the car was leaking through the Pressure Relief Valve indicating an overload condition with the car.  Calumet responders helped to offload approximately 300 gallons of Naphtha from the car to create vapor space in the car to stop the release.  Residual Naphtha on the car quickly evaporated once the release was stopped.  Calumet removed the tote of removed naphtha and the car was then moved back to Calumet's facility for additional reduction and inspection.  Remediation consists of track panel removal and excavation of impacted soils.
column169: The shipper should ensure that proper loading procedures are followed including ensuring that adequate outage remains in the tank to allow for expansion and contraction of the product that may occur in transportation.

column168: Tank car UTLX 130056 was reported releasing vapor in the BNSF Railyard at Beaumont, TX on 5/11/2017.  The BNSF responder  reported leak source was at UTLX 130056's manway lid.  After inspection it was verified that the manway lid four bolts were less than tool tight.  BNSF Railway responder properly secured the manway lid bolts and tool tightened the manway swing bolts which mitigated the release.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While waiting to unload, a slow minor drip from the bottom valve cap was observed by facility personnel. Facility personnel told the driver, who donned the appropriate PPE and tightened the cap on the bottom valve, stopping the drip. The drip never reached the ground at the facility, so no ground cleanup was required. The driver then proceeded to the off-loading bay, and was offloaded without further incident. The incident was reported to Jamie Gonzalves at the Massachusetts DEP; no report number was issued.     It was determined upon investigation that the bottom valve knife valve was not fully seated due to debris. In addition, the bottom valve cap was determined to be not fully tightened by the driver.
column169: The driver in this incident was retrained on doing in-transit vehicle inspections, and proper techniques for using valve caps, and cap locking devices. The driver was also issued a formal disciplinary write-up. In addition, the branch has changed its standing operational procedures to include using a locking device on all outlet caps (velcro strap, locking pins, or duck tape).

column168: Approximately 6 gallons of UN1993 "N-Butoxymethyl Acrylamide Solution" released from a 55 gallon metal drum that appeared to be punctured by a forklift during loading activities. ON MAY 8, 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 04:10AM A UPS EMPLOYEE IN THE PARSIPPANY FACILITY WITNESSED FLAMES COMING FROM A PACKAGE THAT WAS LOADED IN A STAGED PACKAGE CAR IN THE UPS PARSIPPANY FACILITY. AT APPROXIMATELY 05:21 AM THE ALL CLEAR WAS GIVEN AND ALL EMPLOYEES RETURNED TO WORK. THE FIRE WAS CONTAINED TO THE ONE PACKAGE CAR

column168: On May 31, 2017,  XPO Logistics (XSW Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN3266, PE-12, 8, II (PRO# 762186224) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel discovered (1) 5 gallon poly pail of product with a crack on the dock. It is unknown what caused the crack. Approximately 2 pints of product was released to the box and dock floor. Following a review of the incident and the reported material involved, ERTS has obtained and reviewed the MSDS with the caller. The terminal personnel stated that they are capable, confident and able to clean the release and will wear the provided PPE and over pack the damaged freight into a 55 gallon poly drum in OS & D.

column168: SIX, ONE GALLON JUGS SHIPPED IN A NON-UN SPEC OR SEAL CERTIFIED BOX. CAPS WERE TAPED TO THE CONTAINER, BUT THE CAPS WERE STILL LOOSE AND BEGAN TO LEAK. THREE OF THE 6 JUGS WERE DOUBLE BOXED, BUT THEY ALL LEAKED. THERE WAS INSUFFICIENT CUSHIONING USED TO KEEP CONTENTS FROM SHIFTING OR FALLING OVER.
column169: USE UN SPEC PACKAGING FOR SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS,USE ENOUGH CUSHIONING TO KEEP CONTENTS FROM SHIFTING, AND CHECK CAPS TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE NOT DEFECTIVE BEFORE SHIPPING. ORIGIN ALSO NEEDS TO CHECK PACKAGES WITH HAZARDOUS MARKINGS FOR HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS.

column168: THE RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO DOOR 1 FOR A HAZMAT LEAKER. WEARING PROPER PPE AND IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS, THE RESPONDER CONTAINED THE SPILL AND BROUGHT IT TO SERVICE CENTER FOR PROCESSING.
column169: TIGHTEN AND SEAL THE CAPS ON CONTAINER.

column169: PACKAGE HANDLING

column169: CONTACT SHIPPER FOR PROPER PACKAGING

column168: LEAKING FLAMMABLE HAZARDOUS PACKAGE DISCOVERED ON BOXLINE 2 SLIDE. FIRST RESPONDER RESPONDED AND REMOVED PACKAGE TO DMP AREA FOR PROCESSING. BOTTLE OF LIQUID HAD A LOOSE LID.
UNLOADER DISCOVERED PACKAGE AT REAR DOOR OF TRAILER. THE HAZMAT PACKAGE WAS UPSIDE DOWN.

THE UNLOADER IN DOOR 20 NOTICED THAT LIQUID WAS COMING FROM A HAZMAT PACKAGE INSIDE THE TRAILER. HE LEFT THE TRAILER   NOTIFIED THE NEAREST SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR NOTIFIED THE DESIGNATED RESPONDERS. WHEN I ARRIVED TO THE AREA, I UTILIZED MY DECISION TREE/RESPONSE SHEETS TO ASSESS THE SITUATION. I CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TRAY. I USED CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT TO SOLIDIFY ANY LIQUID ON THE FLOOR. BECAUSE I COULD SEE THAT THERE WAS AT LEAST 1 MORE PACKAGE IN THE NEXT WALL, I BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER. I CHECK ALL PACKAGES THAT HAD BEEN LOADED NEAR THE PACKAGE   FOUND ONE TO BE CONTAMINATED BY THE PRODUCT. I THEN SWEPT UP ALL CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT   ADDED IT TO THE SPILL TRAY. I THEN TOOK THE PACKAGES TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. WHEN I OPENED THE BOX, I FOUND THAT 1 OF THE 4 BOTTLES INSIDE HAD A LOOSE CAP   THAT THE REMAINING 3 BOTTLES WERE CONTAMINATED BY THE PRODUCT.
PACKAGE FELL OFF BELT AND STARTED LEAKING JAIME AVILA RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE.
column169: BETTER PACKAGE HANDLING

column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT, SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION, AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE, AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDE ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE, AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: TILX 101015 was reported leaking by PTRA crews at approximately 1055 hours on Sunday, May 21, 2017 at the Port Terminal Railroad Association, Manchester Yard track 26. Waybill indicates the tank contains UN1832, Sulfuric Acid, Spent. Shell Chemical Co was notified and they dispatched OMI Env. Solutions responder, Travis Hudson, to the scene. OMI was on scene at approximately 1130 hours and found product leaking from the liquid line flange area. 4 of 8 bolts were found to be loose. OMI personnel tightened the bolts to 165 pounds and observed car for additional leakage. None was observed so they neutralized the product on the top and sides of the rail car. The scene was cleared at 1233 hours.     This car is part of a series of cars that operate between Shell Chemical Deer Park and ECO Services Houston. The cars travel under load in both directions approximately 8 miles one way.
column169: Shell Chemical is investigation the cause of the leak and working on a plan to test and prevent product from leaking when the tank pressures up after loading.

column168: At about 9:40 a.m. on 5/25/17 UTLX 956486 was being prepared for transloading. The employees unsealed the dome lid and verified that the valves were closed by visual inspection/hand testing the valves. Upon loosening the plug from the A-end liquid valve, the employees encountered a small amount of residual pressure behind the plug, which was bled off. Once that stopped, the employee loosened the valve plug by an additional two turns. There was an indication of more pressure behind the plug, upon discovery of which the employee immediately ceased loosening the plug. However, the plug was suddenly and violently forced out of the threads. The uncontrolled release of product lasted for approximately 7 hours. Businesses with 1/2 mile of the release were evacuated. Emergency responders were able to close the valve using a cheater-bar to assist them.
column169: The valve involved in this incident is of the Midland 721 type valve, which is a valve known by DOT to be problematic. Service bulletins have been issued, however bulletins should be issued advising of additional operating procedures that should be undertaken to ensure transload employee safety. We have instituted revised procedures designed to identify these problematic valves before transloading activities even begin, together with a multi-level check designed to alert of potential valve failure.

column168: Holston Gases propane bobtail was involved in a head-on collision on KY90 near Monticello, KY.  Accident was caused when a passenger vehicle crossed the centerline hitting the Holston truck.  Impact from the accident resulted in the bobtail overturning on the shoulder of the highway.  Accident damaged one of liquid valves on the truck.  The Holston Gases Monticello branch manager arrived at the scene within 10 minutes of the accident and discovered that the liquid valve was leaking propane vapor(gas).  He was able to get the valve to shut-off at which point no additional propane was released.  Note that no propane liquid was released from the valve (vapor only) because the liquid in the tank was not in contact with the valve because the truck was lying on its side.
column169: From all indications, this incident was handled efficiently and professionally by Holston Gases personnel and emergency response personnel.  Due to the nature of this accident (head-on collision) it is difficult to determine what actions could be taken to prevent a similar situation in the future.

column168: On 5/25/17 our tank farm employee was assigned to load 2200 gallons of Nitric Acid 52% into tank trailer 93.  This tanker holds 2500 Gallons.    Upon safely filling the tanker it was scaled out and moved into our loaded line in our yard.  At 950am one of our tank farm employees noticed a leak spilling from the tanker 93.  The employee called for help and donned appropriate PPE, once help arrived the 1st employee began to investigate the leak.  He opened the outlet box on the tanker and found the internal, external and outlet cap open.  He closed the valves and the leak stopped.    Then the employee moved to the containment drain and put the cover over the drain.    A few minutes later it was decided that the spill was to large to clean up by our internal crew and the site security officer called 911 for Hazmat help and EnviroCare to come in and clean up spill.  The fire dept arrived and they closed 800 South and evacuated the building.  Once Envirocare came onsite at appx 1230pm the evacuated employees were allowed back into the building to gather their personal belongings and leave the area.    ENvircare cleaned up the spill with water.  The entire contents of the cleanup were contained in two liquid storage tanks.  The product will be disposed of correctly once profile is complete.
column169: Investigation highlights:  Tanker just returned from testing and wash out.  when tankers are returned the valves are left open for drying  Evidence shows this is a employee error as he did not close the valves as per our training and checklist requires.  5 whys:  Procedure - Hazard overlooked.  Human - Complacent  Corrective action:  retrain all employees to the proper use of the checklist and to check all valves prior to and after filling.  Label tankers and create diagram to help employees understand where all valves are.

column168: CO-ALLIANCE VEHICLE WAS EASTBOUND ON STATE ROAD 2. PRIVATE CITIZEN THAT WAS WESTBOUND ON STATE ROAD 2, CROSSED CENTER LINE AND STRUCK THE CO-ALLIANCE VEHICLE. UPON IMPACT, CO-ALLIANCE VEHICLE WAS DAMAGED, LEFT THE ROADWAY AND ROLLED DOWN THE DITCH EMBANKMENT. THE FILL LINE ON THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK WAS DAMAGED IN ROLLOVER, RESULTING IN MINOR VAPOR RELEASE THAT OCCURRED FOR APPROXIMATELY 9.5 HOURS. WRECKER COMPANY RECOVERED CARGO TANK FROM DITCH. PROPANE WAS TRANSFERRED TO AN EMPTY CARGO TANK FOR SAFE TRANSPORT. WRECKER COMPANY THEN TRANSPORTED THE UNPRESSURIZED CARGO TANK TO THEIR SECURED PROPERTY FOR INSPECTION BY THE INDIANA STATE POLICE.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A DECLARED DG, A UN 3373, BIOLOGICAL SUBSTANCES CATERGORY B. HOWEVER, AN EMPLOYEE AT THE FEDEX OFFICE LOCATION SUSPECTED THAT IT CONTAINED DRY ICE DUE TO THE COLD FROM THE PACKAGE AND THE FIBERBOARD WAS DAMAGED AND SEEMED TO CONTAIN DRY ICE. A MANAGER OPENED THE PACKAGE TO CONFIRM THE CONTENTS AND DRY ICE PELLETS WERE INSIDE KEEPING THE CONTENTS COLD. THERE WAS NO DRY ICE MARKINGS OR LABELING SO IT'S BELIEVED TO BE UNDECLARED DRY ICE. THIS WAS A COMBINATION PACKAGE WITH AN OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX AND MULTIPLE INNER RECEPTACLES CONTAINING THE UN3373. PHOTOS WERE TAKEN FRO FAA ANF FORWARDED TO DEBORAH KENNEDY FOR THE FAA INVESTIGATION.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: THE THREE PIECE SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AT A FEDEX OFFICE STORE ON COMMERCIAL STREET IN SALEM OR. THE FEDEX OFFICE EMPLOYEE ASKED THE PERSON DROPPING OFF THE BOXES IF THEY CONTAINED DRY ICE. THE REPLY WAS NO, ONLY GEL PACKS. WHEN THE FEDEX EXPRESS EMPLOYEE BROUGHT THE BOXES BACK TO FEDEX EXPRESS FOR PROCESSING, THE BOXES WERE COLD TOP THE TOUCH AND SUBSEQUENTLY OPENED. EACH OF THE THREE BOXES CONTAINED DRY ICE. THERE WAS NO MARKINGS, LABELING, OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO ED STEWART.

column168: While exiting the freeway, the exit ramp had a 25 mph turn at end of it. The driver did not slow to that speed, which resulted in the vehicle rolling over. The cargo tank trailer ruptured, caught on fire, and was completely consumed. The gasoline that did release, was completely consumed by the fire as well.
column169: Due to the fatal injuries sustained by the driver, and nothing left of the tractor or tank trailer due to the fire, no interview could be conducted. Law enforcement cleared the driver of any Hours of Service violations for the previous 7 days, Driver Qualification Files and maintenance records were shown to be in compliance as well. The driver was very familiar with the delivery site and using this exit that accesses the delivery location. Given these facts, and the outcome of the accident, we can only speculate that the driver may have suffered some medical issue that impaired his physical ability to slow or stop the truck. This exit ramp was re-designed many years ago to accommodate new business, and many accidents have occurred since.

column168: When the daylight WLE yard crew was switching, they noticed that crude oil was leaking from the manway on car ACFX 71398.  They reported it to the WLE yardmaster who in turn called myself, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for WLE.  I called Gary Welker from American Refining Group to come out and look at the car since they just loaded it at Mineral City, OH which is close to our yard.  When he investigated, it was found that all of the manway bolts were loose.  They were not even hand tight.  He opened the lid to make sure the gasket was OK and it was.  He then tightened all the bolts and installed new seal 971702 on the manway and released the car for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: DRIVER WAS AT THE SMITH SYSTEMS YARD AND NOTICED HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING AROUND THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER MADE THE PROPER NOTIFICATIONS TO HIS COMPANY AND THEN PLACED FLOOR DRY DOWN TO CONTAIN THE RELEASED MATERIAL. ERS OF OHIO WAS DISPATCHED TO THE LOCATION. UPON ARRIVAL ERS OF OHIO USED PH STRIPS AND A 4 GAS METER TO HELP DETERMINE WHAT THE MATERIAL HAZARDS WERE. NEITHER PH OR 4-GAS INDICATED ANY HAZARDS. ERS OF OHIO THEN OPENED UP THE BACK TRAILER DOORS AND CLIMBED INSIDE OT LOCATE THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS. THEY LOCATED A PALLET OF 5-GALLON PAILS CONTAINING HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION HAD SHIFTED DURING TRANSPORTATION. TWO OF THE 5-GALLON BUCKETS HAD RELEASE ALL OF THEIR CONTENTS. ERS OF OHIO PUT FLOOR DRY INSIDE THE TRAILER AROUND THE IMPACTED AREA AND PALLET TO ABSORB THE RELEASE MATERIAL. THEY THEN PLACED ADDITIONAL FLOOR DRY OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER AS A PRECAUTION. THE SHIPPER. STERICYCLE REPACKAGED EVERYTHING ON WEDNESDAY MAY 17TH. AN ESTIMATED AMOUNT OF 10-GALLONS WAS RELEASED TOTAL WITH APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS ON ASPHALT. ON WEDNESDAY MAY 17TH, 2017, STERICYCLE OVERPACKED THE EMPTY CONTAINERS AS WELL AS ALL THE FLOOR DRY THAT WAS INSIDE THE TRAILER FLOOR.
column169: ENSURE THAT ALL FREIGHT IS PROPERLY SLACKED AND SECURED TO THE PALLET. AS WELL AS SECURED PROPERLY INSIDE THE TRAILER.

column168: On May 30, 2017 during unloading operations, terminal personnel discovered that (1) 55-gallon steel drum containing UN1263 Paint "6143 Gray Backer" had become punctured during loading by other freight. Approximately 4-gallons released to the trailer floor on trailer #3196437. No waterways, soils, and drains were reported to have been impacted. The damaged drum and impacted debris was properly overpacked ans staged in OS&D for the terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On May 23, 2017, XPO Logistics (LSX Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1263, Spectracron SEP 2K Yellow Primer, 3, III, (PRO#100397710) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (3216024) from the XDP Terminal, when (1) 255-gallon metal tote was discovered to be leaking. The caller indicated that the tote appears to be leaking from a weld near the valve. Approximately 6 ounces of product has been released to the trailer floor. Terminal personnel have place the tote on the dock with cardboard underneath at this time.Contractors report the transfer process is going smoothly. They generated 4 - 55 gal metal drums thus far, photos attached. Since PPG confirmed the product will be salvageable, they will be labeled accordingly and sent on to the consignee.Contractors report the transfer is complete and they are leaving site, dock supervisor Gus Cervantes approved. They generated (6) - 55 gal metal drums of transferred salvage product labeled accordingly which will be moved on to the consignee, per the shipper PPG. The empty tote was also labeled accordingly. Nonhaz waste generated and staged onsite for XPO to manage:  1 - 55 gal metal drum containing the impacted cardboard, ppe, pads

column168: Carrier driver was North bound on Highway 191. A vehicle traveling south bound on highway 191 entered north bound travel lane and struck carrier head on. Fire started after impact from motor vehicle fuel that involved both vehicles. Both vehicles burned to the ground. Cargo tank melted in the fire and released an estimated 4000 gallons of UN1203 onto the ground and roadway. Soil remediation and replacement of the roadway is underway at this time. Contaminated soil will be excavated and soil replaced according to state environmental standards and disposed of in a licensed landfill. The roadway replacement project will have an estimated completion date of 6/15/17
column169: Carrier and industry peers have experienced multiple crashes of a similar nature on this roadway during nighttime /early morning hours. Carrier will make all efforts to stay off this highway during the time frame previously described to reduce or prevent re-occurrence of this incident.

column168: DURING DELIVER AGENT S. ALLY WENT TO THE DG AREA AND REMOVED AWB # 235-62681732 T8/K432.8 SAID SHIPMENT WAS TRANSPORTED FROM THE DG AREA ACROSS THE WAREHOUSE AND PLACED ON THE IMPORT FRONT DOCK BY DOOR NUMBER 3 WHERE DHL (CONSIGNEE) TRUCK WAS PARKED. DHL DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE PIECE WAS LEAKING AND BROUGHT IT TO THE ATTENTION OF THE FORKLIFT DRIVER. IMMEDIATELY MR. ALLY NOTIFIED HIS MOD. VISUAL INSPECTION AND REVIEW OF ERG WAS CONDUCTED. BASED ON THE INFORM IDENTIFY LOCAL PAPD WAS CONTACTED FOR SUPPORT. PAPD (ESU) AND EMT RESPONDED. SITUATION WAS TAKEN OVER BY THE PAPD WHO PROVIDED THE SERVICE OF CLEANING AND REMOVAL. DURING THIS PROCESS OUR WAREHOUSE WAS EVACUATED FROM 1230 THROUGH 1430. EMPLOYEES WITH IMMEDIATE EXPOSURE WERE PROVIDED WITH THE RIGHT VOLUME OF MEDICAL ATTENTION.
column169: INVESTIGATION CONCLUSION IS PRESENTLY UNKNOWN. IT IS EVIDENT THAT SOME KIND OF PUNCTURED WAS THE CAUSE OF SPILLAGE, HOWEVER, THE DEFINED REASON AS TO HOW THIS OCCURRED IS STILL BEING REVIEWED. IRRESPECTIVE OF, THE FORKLIFT EMPLOYEE WILL BE PROVIDED WITH RE-TRAINING. THE RE-TRAINING THAT WILL BE PROVIDED IS DG AWARENESS, HAZARDOUS COMMUNICATIONS AND PROPER FORKLIFT TECHNIQUE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING APPROXIMATELY 68 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THE HOSE COMING LOOSE. THE FREE LIQUID IMPACTED THE PARKING LOT SURFACE OF THE CIRCLE K TRUCK STOP AND IMPACTED A NEARBY STORM DRAIN. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID ON THE IMPACTED PARKING LOT SURFACE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO COMPLETE THE SITE CLEANUP. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED AND INSPECTED THE SITE. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL DEPLOYED ABSORBENT BOOM INSIDE THE IMPACTED STORM DRAIN AND DEPLOYED ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL AS NEEDED. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL RECOVERED THE SPENT ABSORBENTS AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. THREE (3) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE CLEANUP.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, EJ POPE WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY DRIVER. THE DRIVER BROUGHT THE PACKAGE CAR BACK TO THE CENTER FOR A HAZMAT RESPONDER TO RESPOND TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE. I WAS GIVEN THE REFERENCE NUMBER "866540" AND I SENT AN EMAIL TO AIR DANGEROUS GOODS WITH PICTURES OF THE PRODUCT AND UNMARKED BOX. THERE WERE NO INNER SEALS UNDER THE CAP. column168: During a routine roadside tire and load securement check, the driver noticed a drip from the input vacuum hose. The driver donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and deployed a bucket and spill pads to catch any release. A crew in proper personal protective equipment was sent to fully remediate the situation by pumping liquid off the vehicle into a separate tanker, putting a cap onto the input vacuum hose, and cleaning any residual waste on the vehicle and parking lot. The driver then proceeded to his final destination and was offloaded without further incident. This incident was reported to Massachusetts DEP at 15:28 to Joel Rees; no report number was issued.
column169: The driver in this incident was retrained on the proper loading of this type of unit, and the mandatory use of input hose caps and cap locking device on vehicles without an input check valve. The driver was also issued a formal disciplinary write-up. In addition, the branch has changed its standing operational procedures to include input hose caps and cap locking device on this type of vacuum unit.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Facility did not have a dock and was offloading in the parking lot. The driver was using an electric pallet jack to tailgate the freight.  He had successfully removed three totes to the back. On the final tote he was lowering the pallet jack to set the tote down when he accidentally bumped the forward button.  The jack lurched forward just enough to cause the front wheel to drop off the edge.  The tote slid off the pallet onto the ground. The tote fell approximately 4 feet to the ground and landed on its side.  The tub was ruptured and started leaking.  The personnel at the facility did not have enough supplies to contain a spill of this size but put down as much floor dry as possible to contain the spill.  The driver called the fire department was called and we were told they didn't have a haz mat crew and told him to call a professional clean up crew.  We contacted Veolia.  When our manager got on site, he called the fire department again and requested they come out.  They arrived and began containing the spill.  They attempted to turn the container over to put the split side up, but that caused the container to rip and gush out the rest of the solution.  The EPA and Veolia arrived and began the clean up.
column169: We have informed our customer that we will no longer offload these tubs to parking lots and will only do dock to dock deliveries.  This was the first time we had done this run and were not told this was going to be off loaded to a parking lot.      Personnel received training to make sure all information on deliveries is received at the time a load is booked.  Driver received remedial training.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the temporary storage, it was discovered that approximately 8 ounces of material had escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container. Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container contents into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the generator has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required  specifications.

column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: A transformer was picked up at customer site and secured using chains to the flatbed.  During the loading and securing process no indication of leakage was visible.  Subsequent load checks were performed as prescribed with no leaking visible.  The driver was pulled in for a roadside inspection conducted by CHP.  At that time it was noted 4 or 5 residue oil drips were visible on the transformer.  No oil landed on the pan / floor of trailer.  The officer told the driver to wipe down the transformer.  The driver wiped down the transformer, taped a plastic bag around the gaskets, placed and taped absorbent pads and plastic at base of transformer.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during all facets of transportation.  IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to insure all transformers are thoroughly drained before loading and transporting occur.  All drivers at this terminal will be retrained on how to spot bad gaskets on transformers.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Our driver was beginning the loading process when he reached for the loading facilities product loading line which included a blow down valve.  Our driver observed a small leak coming from that blow down valve.  He informed the facility's loading operator of the leak.  The operator questioned where the leak was coming from.  Our driver touched the blow down valve to show the operator the location of the leak.  The blow down valve separated from the loading line resulting in a spill of sulfuric acid. Even though our driver was fully attired in complete PPE he sustained chemical burns to his check and neck.    A post incident inspection was performed and determined that the blow down valve was misaligned which resulted in the internal threads being stripped.  The plant installed a new blow down assembly which eliminated the hazard.
column169: Ensure the proper installation is performed on all equipment involved in the loading process at the loading facility.

column168: HXIU 630458 was noted to be leaking when the container arrived in San Bernardino. The container was moved to the Haz pit and awaited a contractor for clean-up. The container was only marked as "FAK" on the waybill as all HAZ inside this container was undeclared on the waybill. The original contractor arrived and found the leaking HAZ inside the container and that contractor withdrew as it was beyond their practices. There was an approximate 5-gallon loss of product. The container was cleaned and the spill remediated.

column161: ANTHONY SENIOR VICE PRESIDENT, TRANSPORTATION COMP
column168: During a routine facility inspection, and tote was found to have a very small amount of pooled liquid under its fill cap. No leakage was observed by the driver at the time the container was accepted by the transporter.    A field service response crew was summoned; wearing the correct personal protective equipment, the crew removed the tote cap and gasket, neutralized and cleaned the residue from the tote, and installed a new cap and gasket on to the tote. The waste generated from the cleanup was disposed of in the appropriate waste stream. The tote continued on to its final destination without further incident.       The tote cap was found to have been properly secured and locked. The cap gasket was found to have been defective, allowing the cap to weep.     The release was reported to the Michigan DEP PEAS line at 17:19 5/16/17; no report number was issued.
column169: The generator was made aware of the issue, and instructed to train its employees to more carefully inspect each tote closure before use. The transporter’s driver and facility personnel were retrained to be more diligent with inspecting drums, packages, and totes, before accepting these items for transportation, and during all phases of the transportation process.

The car was secured and waiting for transfer.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS & ER
column168: ON 5/4/17, THE SWRU 947572 WAS FOUND TO HAVE VISIBLE SPARKING ON THE CONTAINER DURING RAMPING OPERATIONS AT THE BNSF PORTLAND HUB CENTER. THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND PLACED IN THE HAZMAT PIT FOR FURTHER INSPECTION BY A CONTRACTOR. THE CONTAINER WAS LISTED AS CONTAINING FAK (STCC: 4611110). UPON INSPECTION, THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE CONTAINER LOADED WITH LEAD ACID BATTERIES SECURED ON PALLETS AND SHRINK WRAPPED. THE CONTAINER WAS UNLOADED AND A PALLETT WAS FOUND WITH SIDE TERMINALS ON A BATTER THAT WERE IN CONTACT WITH SIDE OF THE STEEL CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS SHORTING OUT THE TERMINALS. THE SHORT HAD CAUSED HOLES TO BE BURNED THROUGH THE CONTAINER.   BECAUSE THE TERMINALS WERE NOT PROTECTED FROM SORTING OUT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BATTERY EXEMPTION (49CFR 173.159E) DID NOT APPLY AND IS THEREFORE DEEMED AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT.  THE CONTRACTOR CORRECTED THE DEFICIENCY TO PROTECT THE TERMINALS, RELOADED THE CONTAINER AND THE SHIPMENT CONTINUED IN TRANSPORTATION USING THE EXEMPTION.
column169: THE SHIPPER SHOULD ENSURE THAT TERMINAL OF BATTERIES ARE PROPERLY PROTECTED PRIOR TO TENDERING SHIPMENTS FOR TRANSPORTATION.

On 05/30/2017, at 0138 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered SCMX 4137, a loaded tank car of Isoprene, leaking from the protective housing. The car was isolated and Shell Chemical Company, the National Response Center, and the West Virginia Department of Environmental Protection were notified. CHEMTREC Report 2017-05-30-00023). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the A-End Liquid Line Valve partially open and the secondary closure plug not secured. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Jeffrey Bowes, 403-465-0547. Contractor personnel secured the open valve and secondary closure plug. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.

column168: Carrier driver observed hazmat on the sides of the CMTV while making a turn off the highway.  The product was observed coming out of rear clean out port on the CTMV.  We are still currently investigating the cause of the failure and will file a follow up supplemental report.    The duration of the release occured no longer than one minute.  The hazmat release ceases when the CTMV is at a stop and the product is below the opening of the port.  A replacement cap was placed on the port.         Quality Event #64658.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. PICKUP TRUCK SWERVED INTO LANE OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT, RESULTING IN AN ACCIDENT. AS A RESULT, THE VEHICLE LEFT THE ROADWAY, OVERTURNED AND CAUGHT ON FIRE. THE MAURY COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE ASSESS THE SITE. HEPACO, INC. WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. HEPACO, INC. INSPECTED THE SITE AND DISCOVERED A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF HOT ASPHALT OIL AND 30 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. HEPACO, INC. DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO RECOVER THE FREE LIQUID ON THE IMPACTED ASPHALT ROADWAY SURFACE.    HEPACO, INC. RETURNED TO THE SITE ON MAY 19, 2017. HEPACO EXCAVATED AN AREA OF IMPACTED SOIL APPROXIMATELY 30 FEET BY 30 FEET. HEPACO, INC. COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, GRAMMER INDUSTRIES, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column162: SVP HEALTH, SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: Material was noticed leaking from a parked van trailer onto the gravel parking lot. An internal emergency response team was mobilized and responded. Upon arrival the ER team donned level D PPE and supplied air before entering the trailer. The leaking package was identified and it was determined that the leak had abated. The trailer was moved into an available dock where it was offloaded and the damaged package was overwrapped. The remaining leaked material was cleaned from the ground and inside of the trailer and properly disposed of.
column169: A number of failures were noted which led up to this release. A faulty internal process at the generator led to free liquid remaining in the filter cake. Further, the pallet used to transport the material was in poor condition which may have led to the puncture. The driver who originally transported the material admitted noticing the bag looked "heavier" than the others on the shipment but failed to act or notify management. the generator has instituted an improved process to more completely eliminate free liquids in their filter cake. Drivers have been re-trained with regard to reporting abnormal circumstances to their managers.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Human Error
column168: Fuel truck driver swerved to avoid another vehicle coming across the center line of the road from opposite direction, overcompensated steering of fuel truck, and turned over on its side and left the road way to the road side.  Diesel fuel in fuel truck left the tank by way of a pencil sized air valve (?) on truck top until found and stopped up by crew arriving.  An environmental crew in area arrived on site and started containment and clean up, of diesel volumes released  (estimated to be 1,000 gallons of which all were recovered) by using absorbent diapers/pads, stopping leaking valve at the time of arrival, and an emergency response company was called to assist in clean up and recovery by use of a vacuum truck to remove liquid spilled.
column169: Training on this construction spread with a safety stand down was held company wide with-in days of this incident occurrence, stressing defensive driving, contributing factors as mud on drivers boots may have contributed to foot slipping off brake.  Narrow steep roads in mountainous terrain were discussed and to insure other company drivers understood narrow road and situation to prevent in future.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TOM CHAMBERS (CARTERENERGY TRANSPORT DRIVER) REPORTED A DIESEL FUEL SPILL TO RICK TRACY (CARTERENERGY DISPATCHER) WHILE DELIVERING TO THE CITY OF OLATHE MAINTENANCE FACILITY 1415 S ROBINSON ST OLATHE KS AT 4:45PM ON 5-5-17. TOM STATED THAT HE WAS PUMPING OFF DF FROM COMPARTMENT #2 ON HIS TRANSPORT INTO A 10000 GALLON ABOVE GROUND DOUBLE WALL TANK WHEN HE SAW DF RUNNING UNDER THE NL TANK WHICH IS SITUATED BETWEEN THE TRANSPORT AND THE DF TANK AND ONTO THE PARKING LOT CURB. ONCE TOM SAW THE FUEL HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF HIS FUEL TRANSFER PUMP AND CLOSED THE TANKER COMPARTMENT VALVES. HE GRABBED ABSORBENT PADS AND FLOOR DRY FROM HIS TRAILER AND A SPILL MATERIAL BOX ADJACENT TO THE TANK ALONG THE CURB AND UNDER THE TANK TO TRY AND CAPTURE THE FUEL. HE CONTACTED DISPATCH TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AND CALLED TIM SZIPPL (CARTERENERGY SAFETY MANAGER) WHO ARRIVED AT APPROX 5:45PM. THE DF TANK WAS COMPLETELY FULL AND A HOSE WITH A PIPE WAS INSERTED INTO THE VENT OPENING AT THE TOP OF THE TANK TO REMOVE 1318 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE TANK BACK INTO THE TRANSPORT UNIT. ALL FREE STANDING PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS REMOVED WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND PLACED INTO BUCKETS FOR DISPOSAL OFF SITE. THE GRASS AREA UNDER THE TANKS HAS BEEN SATURATED FROM RECENT RAINS AND THERE’S A CLAY SOIL UNDERLINING APPX 2” UNDER THE GRASS SO PENETRATION INTO THE GROUND SHOULD BE MINIMIZED. STEVE NELSON (NIGHT MAINTENANCE SUPERVISOR) AT THE FACILITY WAS NOTIFIED AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO TEDD HANSEN (MAINTENANCE FACILITY MANAGER). HAZ-MAT RESPONSE IN OLATHE WAS CONTACTED AND MEET WITH CARTERENERGY PERSONNEL AT 9AM ON MONDAY 5-8-17 TO DISCUSS CONTAMINATED SOIL REMOVAL AND REMEDIATION. A TOTAL OF 71 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS UNACCOUNTED FOR AND THAT AMOUNT WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT#1177600) AND THE KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT (KDHE REPORT#41561). CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED ON 5-9-17 AND DISPOSED OF PER KDHE GUIDELINES. DRIVER DELIVERED TO WRONG CITY OR OLATHE FACILITY. HE SHOULD HAVE DELIVERED TO THE SOUTH ROBINSON DRIVE FACILITY IN OLATHE. ADDITIONALLY THE TANK GAGE STUCK AND GAVE FALSE READING TO THE DRIVER.
column169: REPAIR DEFECTIVE TANK GAGE AND RETRAIN DRIVER ON VERIFYING CORRECT DELIVERY ADDRESS BEFORE UNLOADING ANY PRODUCT.

ON 05/26/2017, A MC307 CARGO TANK WAS LOADED WITH SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, PARKED AT THE TRIMAC TRANSPORTATION FAIRBURN YARD WAITING FOR DELIVERY. AFTER BEING LOADED, THE CARGO TANK HAD BEEN PARKED FOR APPROXIMATELY 30-45 MINUTES WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE CENTER OF THE TRAILER. A CONTAINMENT BARREL WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP AND A CLEAN TRAILER WAS LOCATED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT. A SMALL CONTAMINATED AREA ON THE GROUND WAS DUG UP AND PLACED IN THE CONTAINMENT BARREL.     AFTER AN INVESTIGATION, THE BARREL WAS FOUND TO HAVE SEVERAL PITS AND ONE PIT HAD WORN THROUGH CAUSING THE LEAK.
column169: CONTINUE TO COMPLETE SCHEDULED TESTING REQUIREMENTS WHICH MEET THE REGULATION STANDARD ON CARGO TANKS.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT,LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, HE MISTAKENLY OPENED A VALVE ON THE TRAILER PRIOR TO CONNECTING THE HOSE TO THE STORAGE TANK. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KENAN TRANSPORT,LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column161: ANTHONY SENIOR VICE PRESIDENT, TRANSPORTATION COMP
column168: The driver arrived to offload a 9000 gallon delivery of waste oil fuel to the customers 15,000 gallon tank. Before beginning the off load, he was told by facility personnel that the tank gauge showed there to be sufficient space for the entire load. In the process of unloading, the driver noticed the tank gauge giving a much higher reading than was expected at the point. While in the process of verifying his remaining load and re checking the facility tank gauge some distance away, the facility tank was over filled. The original tank gauge reading was found to be incorrect. All of the released fuel oil was captured in containment, with no release to soil or water. A field service crew, equipped with the correct PPE, was dispatched to pump out the fuel oil from containment, and fully degrease and remediate the containment structure. All generated cleanup waste was drummed, and manifested to the appropriate waste stream for disposal.     The release was reported to the NYS DEC to operator David 585, report # 1701770.
column169: The NYS DEC did a facility inspection after this release and recommended a revised overflow protection safety system for the facility. The driver has also been retrained on doing blind or distance off loads, specifically as to when it might be necessary to find additional assistance during an offload.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: ODYSSEY MANUFACTURING CO. REVIEWED ITS RECORD AND OFFERS THE FOLLOWING ACCOUNT OF AN INCIDENT THAT OCCURRED ON MAY 3, 2017 AT AROUND 1500 IN THE AFTERNOON. OUR DRIVER HAD COMPLETED FILLING A 2,100 -GALLON SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TANK MANUFACTURED BY NORWESCO LOCATED AT THE CITY OF WINTER HAVEN WINTERSET WATER TREATMENT PLANT. THE TANK IS LOCATED INSIDE A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA. THE TANK MEASURES 87” IN DIAMETER AND IS 89’” THE TANK WAS FILLED TO 2,000 GALLONS. AFTER THE DRIVER DISCONNECTED THE FILL HOSE HE NOTICED A SMALL AMOUNT (FEW OUNCES) OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SPILLED OUT OF THE FILL LINE ON THE GROUND AFTER THE DRIVER STARTED THE FILL HOSE ON HIS TANKER, HE NOTICED THAT SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE BEGAN RUNNING OUT OF THE FILL LINE ON THE GROUND. THE DRIVER THEN CUPPED THE END OF THE FILL LINE TO STOP THE LEAK. BASED ON A DROP OF AN INCH OR SO IN THE TANK LEVEL, WE ESTIMATE THAT 30 GALLONS WAS SPILLED. THE CITY OF WINTER HAVEN WATER PLANT EMPLOYEE TOLD THE ODYSSEY DRIVER TO GO AND HE WOULD REPORT THE INCIDENT TO HIS MANAGEMENT AND DO ANY CLEANUP AND ANY OTHER REQUIRED ACTIONS SINCE THE CITY OF WINTER HAVEN WAS THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY FOR IT’S TANK AND PROPERTY (AND NOT ODYSSEY).
column169: WHAT APPARENTLY HAPPENED IS THAT THE NEWLY INSTALLED FILL LINE DROPS DOWN INTO THE TOP OF THE TANK AND DOES NOT HAVE A VALVE ON THE END. AT THE END OF THE DELIVERY, SOME OF THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE BACK-SIPHONED OUT OF THE TANK THROUGH THE FILL LINE. UNFORTUNATELY, THE END OF THE HARD PIPED FILL LINE IS LOCATED OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT SO THE SIPHONED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND AND INTO THE SOIL ON THE CITY OF WINTER HAVEN’S PROPERTY. AFTER THE INCIDENT, I DISCOVERED THESE ISSUES WITH STEVE WORDER OF THE CITY OF WINTER HAVEN (WHO OWNS THE TANK AND FACILITY) AND HE AGREED TO CORRECT THOSE INSTALLATION PROBLEMS (FILL LINE EXTENDING DOWN INTO THE TANK, NO VALVE ON THE END OF THE FILL LINE, AND THE END OF THE FILL LINE OUTSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA). SO THE CANNOT OCCUR AGAIN. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE PROPERTY AND WITH ALL THE RAIN FLUIDS HAS BEEN GETTING THERE WAS NO IMPACT TO THE LOCAL SOIL AND THE GRASS HAS SINCE REGROWN.

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 5/29/17 at approximately 23:13, an ammonia odor was reported in the Spokane yard by yard employees.  The area was immediately isolated and operations in the general area where suspended while the response and investigation was occurring.  Four Anhydrous Ammonia cars were found to be together in the yard and the inspection focused on these cars given the location and details from the crew.  The Spokane Fire Hazmat Team, BNSF Hazmat Team and contract responders arrived on-scene.  The Fire Department initiated air monitoring at the BNSF property boundary and at nearby residences, no ammonia odor was identified and no monitoring readings were observed.  BNSF Hazmat and contract responders inspected the four cars and found the ACFX 220507 with a very small leak detected with air monitoring equipment in the protective housing.  No odor or air monitoring results were observed at ground level.  The leak was found to be originating from between the vapor valve and pressure plate.  2 of 4 valve flange bolts were tightened by less than 1/8 of turn and the leak stopped as verified by air monitoring (gastech tubes and PID).    Later in the day on 5/30/17 while the car was being moved within yard limits, yard crews reported an ammonia odor coming from the car.  The area was again isolated and responders were dispatched to the yard.  The leak was again found to be coming from the vapor valve flange.  The flange bolts were not able to be tightened any further.  It was determined that the car would need to be transferred and vapor removed from the car.  Preparations were made to transfer the car and control vapors by vacuum through water until pressure was removed the car.  The car was transferred on 5/31/17 with cleaning and purging occuring between 5/31/17 and 6/2/17.  The car was then transported to shop under an OTMA-3 provided by CF Industries.    The release volumes indicated in this report are estimates only and based upon observations during the response, the gauging device on this car was disabled and volume measurements were not available during this incident.  The root cause of the release is not known at this time, it will be investigated by the car owner/lessee.
column169: The yet to be completed root cause determination will ultimately determine what further actions should be taken.

Facility personnel discovered a small leak of Delpac 2000 from a fitting on Univar tanker #16299. An estimated 5 gallons was lost onto an asphalt parking area. The spilled material was collected with absorbents and was not immediately reportable to government agencies.     The leak was traced to failure of a metal nipple that was located on the outside, bottom of the tank on the vehicle.  The nipple was made of mild steel and should have been made of stainless steel.  The fitting was replaced which allowed the truck to go back into service. There were no injuries during the incident.  The truck was manufactured in October 2016.

column168: ON 5/2/17 DURING TRANSFER OF K048 WASTE (DGF FLOAT) FROM A FRAC TANK TO A TANKER TRUCK, A SMALL AMOUNT (2-3 GAL) OF THE WASTE WAS DISCHARGED FROM THE TRUCK’S VACUUM PUMP VENT TO THE GROUND.    BASED ON AN INVESTIGATION BY THE WASTE DISPOSAL CONTRACTOR (HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL) AND ITS HAULING SUBCONTRACTOR (MID-AMERICA WASTE SOLUTION LLC), THE RELEASE OCCURRED BECAUSE THE K048 WASTE WAS FOAMIER THAN IT NORMALLY IS. AS A RESULT, THE FOAMY PORTION OF THE SOLUTION ENTERED THE SCRUBBER AND, DUE TO THE BUOYANCY OF THE FOAM, DIDN'T ALLOW THE SCRUBBER SHUTOFF VALVE TO ACTIVATE.
column169: CALUMET HAS REVISED ITS PROCEDURE FOR SHIPPING WASTES VIA VACUUM-LOADED TANK TRUCKS TO REQUIRED PROVISION OF CONTAINMENT FOR THE TRUCK’S VACUUM PUMP VENT. IN ADDITION, WHEN WASTES ARE KNOWN OR SUSPECTED TO BE FOAMY LESS WILL BE LOADED INTO THE TRUCK TO ENSURE THAT FOAM DOESN’T ENTER THE SCRUBBER.

column168: THE DRIVER HIT A METAL GRATE COVERING A HOLE IN THE ROAD THAT WAS UNDER CONSTRUCTION. AROUND THE GRATE COVERING WAS 3-4IN OF ASPHALT TO KEEP THE GRATE IN PLACE. WHEN THE GRATE WAS HIT IT CAUSED THE BATTERY PALLET TO COLLAPSE ON THE LEFT FRONT STRINGER. ONCE THIS OCCURRED THE TRUCK STRAPPING BECAME LOOSE AND CAUSED THE BATTERY TO BECOME FREE FROM THE PALLET. THE SHRINK WRAP COVERING THE PALLET COULD ALSO HAVE BEEN A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR.
column169: - PALLETS WITH NO BOTTOM RUNNER CONNECTING THE 3 LONG BOARDS OR STRINGERS WILL (AND HAVE BEEN) ELIMINATED FROM INVENTORY.  - PLASTIC COVERINGS HAVE BEEN REMOVED FROM DIRECT CONTACT WITH BUILT IN COVERS ON BATTERIES. WOOD COVERING IS NOW USED FOR SOME OF OUR BATTERY TYPES THAT WILL PROVIDE A BARRIER AGAINST THE PLASTIC COVERING.  - THE PALLET INTEGRITY IS DOUBLE CHECKED BEFORE THE VEHICLES LEAVE THE FACILITY.

column168: CPS DRIVER WAS DELIVERING AN IBC OF GRAMOXONE SL 2.0 (PARAQUAT DICHLORIDE) TO CUSTOMER’S FARM AND HAD MOVED THE CONTAINER ON THE PALLET JACK TO THE LIFT GATE OF THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK WAS PARKED ON A SLIGHT INCLINE. WHEN HE ROLLED THE PALLET JACK ONTO THE LIFT GATE AND LOWERED IT, THE CONTAINER CONTINUED TO SLIDE AND FELL OFF THE LIFT GATE APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET TO THE GROUND. IT LANDED ON ITS SIDE ON THE CONCRETE PAD, SUSTAINING A CRACK OF <3” IN THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER. PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THE CRACK ONTO THE CONCRETE AND INTO THE SURROUNDING SOIL FOR SEVERAL MINUTES. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET SOME LUMBER UNDER THE CONTAINER TO ELEVATE IT TO STOP THE LEAK AND THEN WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN THE SPILLED MATERIAL TO PREVENT FURTHER SPREADING. HE THEN CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  HE THEN CONTACTED THE CUSTOMER WHO ARRIVED WITH HIS BACKHOE AND THEY WERE ABLE TO FULLY UPRIGHT THE CONTAINER.  THE WAREHOUSE MANAGER CALLED THEIR SISTER LOCATION ORANGEBURG FOR HELP IN REPORTING SINCE HE WAS ON HIS WAY TO THE SCENE WITH THE SPILL KIT. THE MANAGER OF THE CPS TERMINAL IN ORANGEBURG MADE THE NOTIFICATION CALLS AND PROCEEDED TO THE SCENE. ALL THREE OF THESE INDIVIDUALS, DRIVER, WAREHOUSE MANAGER, AND TERMINAL MANAGER ARE TRAINED TO INCIDENT COMMANDER LEVEL IN HAZWOPER. THEY WORKED TOGETHER TO ESTABLISHED THEIR ZONES AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. LEPC PERSONNEL FROM BARNWELL COUNTY, SC AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM SC DHEC WERE PRESENT AT THE SITE AND APPROVED THE CLEAN UP.  MATERIAL WAS PUMPED FROM THE CRACKED IBC INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER AND WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO CPS ORANGESBURG, CROSSCREEK ROAD.
column169: WE DISCUSSED THIS INCIDENT WITH ALL OF OUR DELIVERY DRIVERS TO INCREASE AWARENESS OF THE HAZARDS OF DELIVERING IBC’S WHEN USING A PALLET JACK AND LIFT GATE. THEY SHOULD BE CONSCIOUS OF HOW THEY ARE PARKED AND WHAT HAZARDS COULD PREVENT THEM FROM SAFELY UNLOADING THE PRODUCT.

CN Transportation department employee reported vapors coming from the top of tank car TILX 111216 (Residue / HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during switching operations at CN Geismar Yard, Geismar, LA. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting vapors coming from the top of the railcar.  Upon closer inspection, vapors were observed coming from the fill hole cover.  The bolts were checked and 2 of the 3 were found to be loose.  The bolts were tightened and the leak stopped.  The top of the car was neutralized. Tank car released for movement.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: CN mechanical department employee noted an odor coming from tank car TILX 304679 (Load/Anhydrous Ammonia, UN1005) during an inspection at the CN Harrison Yard, Memphis, TN. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting all closures were closed and seals intact. The source of the odor was found to be emitting from between the rim nozzle of the car and the pressure plate of the protective housing. Real time air monitoring confirm high levels at the source of the leak and dissipated quickly away from the leak. Further inspection found 5 of the pressure plate mounting nuts were less than tool tight. All pressure plate mounting nuts were tightened or confirmed tool tight. Leak was stopped. Began to transload into UTLX 951256 (provided by CF Industries) but a leak in the liquid line packing gland was discovered and the transload stopped approximately 5 minutes after starting. Attempts to tighten the packing gland proved unsuccessful. Additional Teflon chevron packing glans were shipped in and installed the following day. Transloaded contents from TILX 304679 into SHQX10506 and released for movement to destination. TILX 304679 and UTLX 951256 will be cleaned and purged and set to home shop for repairs.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE, IT WAS A HUMAN ERROR. THE DRIVER WAS DRAINING IBC CONTAINERS IN THE TRUCK TO A TANK AT THE CUSTOMERS FACILITY. THE DRIVER HAD 2 DIFFERENT CHEMICALS IN SEVERAL INDIVIDUAL IBC’S. HE HOOKED UP THE SLACK PLUS IBC AND STARTED TO DRAIN IT INTO THE CUSTOMER’S BLEACH TANK. THE COMBINATION OF THE MIXTURE STARTED TO OFF GAS, CAUSING A CHLORINE GAS SMELL. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE OPERATION AND NOTIFIED EVERYONE WITHIN THE FACILITY TO LEAVE. OUR OWN EMPLOYEE’S ENTERED AND DID THE CLEANUP. IT LASTED APPROXIMATELY 12 HRS.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS SPOKEN TO AND REPRIMANDED FOR THE INCIDENT.  RETRAINING AND FURTHER EDUCATION ON CHEMICAL HAZARDS, TOOK PLACE. SLACK CHEMICAL HAS TAKEN STEPS TO CHANGE THE SIZE OF FITTINGS AND HOSE TO 1” ¾ ON ALL SLACK PLUS I.B.C.’S. TANKS, HOSES, SO THAT IT WOULD BE IMPOSSIBLE FOR THIS TO OCCUR AGAIN. EQUIPMENT AND PARTS ARE ON ORDER, AT THIS TIME.

column169: THIS RUPTURE OCCURRED EVEN THOUGH THE TANKER HAD BEEN INSPECTED LESS THAN 30 DAYS PREVIOUS IN WHICH IT PASSED THE PRESSURE TEST. WE ARE TRAINED TO CHECK FOR LEAKS DURING THE FILLING PROCESS AND NOTICED A DRIP PREVIOUS TO THE RUPTURE AND STARTED PUMPING OUT PRODUCT AND WERE ABLE TO SAVE 800 GALLONS FROM HITTING THE GROUND.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO PICKUP HIS NEXT LOAD AND THE OUR DISPATCHER DID NOT UPDATE THE PROPER EQUIPMENT NEEDED TO TRANSPORT FERRIC CHLORIDE IN THE TRAILER. column168: DRIVER HAD JUST FINISHED LOADING TRUCK AND LEFT THE REFINERY. HE WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON WAYSIDE ROAD AT APPROX 35-40 MPH. THIS IS A NARROW PAVED 2 LANE ROADWAY WITH AN APPROX 12 INCH SHOULDER THAT THEN DROPS DOWN SEVERAL FOOT INTO A FARM FIELD. IT WAS RAINING. THERE WAS ANOTHER VEHICLE TRAVELING SOUTH AND OUR DRIVER FELT THAT OTHER VEHICLE WAS CLOSE TO CENTER LINE – HE ATTEMPTED TO MOVE OVER TO THE RIGHT TO GIVE MORE ROOM, WHEN APPARENTLY THE RL FRONT STEER TIRE DROPPED OFF, PAVEMENT ONTO THE VERY SOFT DIRT SHOULDER. THIS PULLED TRUCK TO THIS POINT – DRIVER UNABLE TO CORRECT AND TRUCK WAS PULLED DOWN STEEP INCLINE AND ROLLED OVER IN THE FARM FIELD. TRUCK CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE. COMPARTMENT 1 OF TRAILER LEAKED SOME PRODUCT FROM THE DOME LID. MINOR LEAK – LEAK WAS STOPPED AT SCENE BY REFINERY EMPLOYEE. NOTE – THIS IS A 5 COMPARTMENT TRAILER.
column169: POOR SITUATION - NARROW ROADWAY. NO SHOULDER. RURAL ROAD. SHOULDER ONLY APPROX 12 INCH WIDE. THE IT DROPS OFF ON A VERY STEEP SCOPE SEVERAL FEET INTO A FARM FIELD. DIRT SHOULDER WAS VERY SOFT DUE TO RECORD HEAVY RAIN. IT WAS RAINING AT TIME OF ACCIDENT.

column168: ACCORDING TO OUR DRIVER, ROBERT WARNER, HE WAS DRIVING EAST BOUND ON HIGHWAY 58 IN SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY WHEN TRAFFIC CAME TO A SUDDEN STOP. THE SUDDEN STOP CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT, AND THREE, 275-GALLON IBC TOTES BROKE FREE IMPACTING ONE ANOTHER, RESULTING IN DAMAGE (PUNCTURES) TO THE CONTAINERS AND THE SUBSEQUENT SPILLAGE OF 100-200 GALLONS OF A REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF RCRA HAZARDOUS (D007) CHROMIUM SOLUTION (MANIFEST 017035454JJK) AND 25-30 GALLONS OF A NON-RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD, NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT, AND DEPLOYED SPILL RESPONSE MEASURES. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT THE CONTAINERS WERE ACTIVELY LEAKING FOR NO MORE THAN 5-10 MINUTES. INITIAL NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE OES (OES REPORT #/ CONTROL #: 17-3477) BY NEIL FRUMKIN ON 05-16-2017 AT 1954 HOURS. A THIRD-PARTY SPILL RESPONSE COMPANY (PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES) WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN-UP OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND CONDUCT THE TRANSFERRING OF MATERIAL FROM DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO NEW CONTAINERS. THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PUNCTURED IN VARIOUS LOCATIONS, SEE THE ATTACHED PHOTOS FOR REFERENCE. THE CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED UNDER THE OBSERVATION OF LOCAL CUPA OFFICIALS. THE SPILL CLEAN-UP GENERATED 10 DRUMS OF ABSORBENT AND SOIL, THE WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED A STORAGE YARD, THE MATERIAL WAS SAMPLED AND ANALYZED, THE ANALYTICAL RESULTS WERE NON-HAZARDOUS. THE WASTE MATERIAL WAS PROFILED AND DISPOSED OF BASED ON THE RESULTING LAB ANALYSIS. THE RQ NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE NRC (NRC INCIDENT REPORT # 1178531) ON 05-17-17 AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00AM, THIS NOTIFICATION WAS MADE BY KEVIN FRANCO AND KEITH CUMMINGS OF ENVIROSERV.
column169: THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS THE WAY IN WHICH THE CONTENTS IN THE TRAILER WERE SECURED. TRAILERS WERE BEING SECURED BASED ON THE INTERPRETATION OF GUIDANCE RECEIVED BY THE LOCAL CHP, IN WHICH DRIVERS WERE INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THAT ALL CONTAINERS WERE STRAPPED TO THE STRUCTURE OF THE TRAILER. USING THIS LOAD SECUREMENT METHODOLOGY INADVERTENTLY CREATED AN ADDITIONAL HAZARD, BECAUSE IT LEFT VOID SPACES IN BETWEEN SOME OF THE CONTAINERS. WHEN THE DRIVER WAS FORCED TO COME TO A HARD STOP, THE LOAD SHIFTED, THE WEIGHT OF THE STRAPPED IBC’S PULLED THE E-RAILS FROM THE STRUCTURE AND THE CONTAINERS IMPACTED ONE ANOTHER RESULTING IN THE DAMAGE TO THE CONTAINERS.   THE ENVIROSERV SAFETY COMMITTEE AND MANAGEMENT REVIEWED THIS INCIDENT AND PERFORMED A FULL ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS. THROUGH THIS EXERCISE WE IDENTIFIED LESSONS LEARNED AND BEST PRACTICES BY WHICH WE DEVELOPED A LOAD SECUREMENT PROCEDURE, TAKING INTO CONSIDERATION THE SPECIFIC TYPES OF LOADS HANDLED BY OUR BUSINESS AND INCORPORATING BEST PRACTICES AND LESSONS LEARNED – ELIMINATING VOID SPACES FROM BETWEEN CONTAINERS – FROM THIS INCIDENT TO MITIGATE FUTURE ISSUES.

column168: THE UNIT WAS DRIVING THROUGH HEFLIN, AL WHEN HE HAD A BLOWOUT. THE TIRE TREAD SLUNG AROUND BREAKING THE FENDER AND WHIPPING THE SIDE VALVE. THE SIDE VALVE CRACKED AT THE BASE CAUSING AC 30 TO LEAK OUT. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF TO A SAFE SHOULDER TO HELP CONTAIN ANY PROBLEMS. THE ONLY LEAK WAS AT THE AT THE SIDE VALVE AND THE CRACK WAS 2 OR 3 INCHES. WE IMMEDIATELY CALLED EMERGENCY SERVICES, WHO IN TURN CALLED CLEBURNE ALDOT. ALDOT BROUGHT SOME SAND FOR CONTAINMENT. ONCE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED, I GOT A HOLD OF ASIMPA FOR THE CLEAN UP. THEY CLEANED DOWN TO FRESH DIRT AND RE-SEEDED.
column169: HONESTLY, I’VE NEVER SEEN A TIRE DO WHAT THIS TIRE DID. I’VE EVEN ASKED A PLETHORA OF FRIENDS IN THE FIELD AND IT WAS NEW TO ALL OF THEM ALSO. I’M GOING WITH FREAK ACCIDENT/DUMB LUCK. AS FOR OUR REACTION TIME, I WAS FAIRLY PROUD. WE HAD EMERGENCY SERVICES THERE WITHIN 15MIN, AND I HAD ASIMPA THERE CLEANING UP THAT MORNING WHILE I TOOK CARE OF THE ADEM AND NRC REPORTS, BY THE WAY WE WERE NO WHERE CLOSE TO ANY WATER. BEST WAY TO DEAL WITH SOMETHING LIKE THIS IS TO HAVE A DRIVER THAT KNOWS WHAT TO DO AND WHERE TO PARK. THEN CALL EMERGENCY SERVICES, WHO WILL TYPICALLY NOTIFY EVERY-ONE YOU NEED TO BE TALKING TOO. THEN HAVE SOMEONE ON THE SCREEN THAT CAN MAKE DECISIONS.

column168: WHITE OIL COMPANY REQUESTED A LOAD OF DYED DIESEL BE TRANSPORTED TO THEIR FACILITY IN ABERDEEN, MS. HOWEVER, THE AMOUNT THEY REQUESTED WAS MORE THAN THEIR ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK COULD CONTAIN. AS REQUESTED CAPITAL TRANSPORT BEGAN FILLING THE TANK AND BECAUSE THE CUSTOMER REQUESTED MORE THAN THE TANK COULD HOLD 1,379 GALLONS OF DYED DIESEL BEGAN FLOWING FROM THE TANK. ACCORDING TO EPA’S SPILL PREVENTION, CONTROL, AND COUNTERMEASURE (SPCC) PROGRAM WHITE OIL COMPANY’S SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SHOULD HAVE HELD THE DIESEL. HOWEVER, THE CONTAINMENT DIKE HAD AN OPENING IN IT AND THE DIESEL WAS RELEASED INTO A NEARBY DITCH. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED AND THE CLEANED UP THE SPILL. THE SPILL NEVER REACHED A WATER BODY.
column169: IF THE TANK OWNER HAD ADEQUATE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AS REQUIRED BY THE EPA, THE RELEASE WOULD HAVE NEVER OCCURRED.

column169: In this case there was a car next to our driver so our driver did not have "an out" to avoid running over the debris in the highway. The trailer load was NOT effected in this incident. The only product loss was from the "saddle bag" of the tractor.

column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER {CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT.WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: DRIVER OF UNIT TRAVELING SOUTH ON I 25. FROM THE DRIVER AND WITNESSES A TIRE BLOWOUT ON THE DRIVERS SIDE CAUSED THE VEHICLE TO VIER TO THE LEFT AT A SHARP ANGLE. THE VEHICLE COLLIDED WITH THE CONCRETE BARRIER. UPON THE IMPACT THE DRIVERS SIDE FUEL TANK RUPTURED. THE VEHICLE PROCEEDED TO GO AIRBORNE ALONG THE WALL. UPON COMING DOWN THE FUEL CONTAINER OF THE 1500 GALLON CAPACITY IS RUPTURED AS WELL. APPROX. 500 GALLONS OF FUEL BEGAN TO SPILL AND IGNITE. EMERGENCY CREWS ARRIVED AND APPLIED A FOAM TO SUPPRESS THE FIRE AND CONTAIN THE REMAINING FLUID.   APPROX DURATION OF RELEASE WAS 45 MINUTES.

column58: Fusible Pressure Relief Device or Element
column168: THE TRAILER WAS FILLED PROPERLY DURING A NORMAL FILLING SEQUENCE AND THEN PROPERLY DISCONNECTED AND PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT. THE TRAILER SAT FOR 1-3 HOURS BEFORE DEPARTURE. AS NORMAL AND PROPER DURING THIS TIME, THE GAS PRESSURE DECREASED AS THE INTERNAL GAS TEMPERATURE DECREASED. THE TRAILER DEPARTED THE SITE, AND AFTER BEING UNDERWAY FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES, THE THERMAL PROTECTION RELIEF DEVICE(S) (TPRD) FOR THE ROW OF THREE CONNECTED CYLINDERS ACTUATED, CAUSING ALL 3 TANKS IN THAT ROW TO START VENTING TO ATMOSPHERE. (NORMAL ACTUATION TEMPERATURE TRIGGER IS 225 DEGF)  THE DRIVER HEARD THE SOUND OF THE VENTING GAS AND PULLED TO THE SIDE OF I-81 VERY NEAR AN EXIT. A PASSING NY STATE TROOPER WAS TRAVELING BY AND PULLED OVER TO ASSESS. THE DRIVER ASSESS THE SITUATION AS A TPRD VENTING ISSUE OF A SINGLE ROW AND RELAYED THIS TO OUR OPERATIONS CENTER. THE TECHNICAL GROUP FROM XNG CONCURRED WITH THE DRIVER’S ASSESSMENT OF THE VENTING. DETERMINATION WAS MADE ON-SITE TO MOVE TRAILER TO THE EXIT OFF-RAMP TO GET IT FARTHER AWAY FROM TRAFFIC FLOW. ONCE THE ROW OF VENTING CYLINDERS EMPTIED, THE TRAILER WAS MOVED OFF OF THE EXIT RAMP TO AN EMPTY LOT 0.5 MILES FROM THE EXIT. A DOT INSPECTION WAS PERFORMED ON THE TRAILER AND IT PASSED. A REVIEW OF THE CYLINDERS AND PIPING SYSTEM WAS COMPLETED. TEMPERATURE AND PRESSURE WERE NORMAL AND VISUAL INSPECTION WAS GOOD.  TECHNICAL DETERMINATION INDICATED THAT ONE OF THE THERMAL DETECTION DEVICES EITHER MALFUNCTIONED OR WAS IMPROPERLY CALIBRATED AT FACTORY, CAUSING THE RELEASE.   TRAILER WAS RELEASED BACK TO XNG.
column169: THE ISSUE SEEMS TO HAVE BEEN A FACTORY SETTING ISSUE ON THE TPRD.   XNG DRIVERS AND OPERATIONS PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN MADE AWARE OF THIS INCIDENT AND HAVE DISCUSSED PROPER WAYS OF HANDLING A FUTURE SIMILAR ISSUE.
